Doc,<br>
  You always assume that everyone agrees it was a &quot;Bad War.&quot;  As I've stated too often, I don't agree that trying to protect a small country from another makes for a bad war.<br>
   The millions that died, because we left attest to the fact that in my opinion it was a &quot;Just War&quot; and as such, I don't need to apologize to anyone.<br>
  I wore my medals with pride. N0--I don't have them on the wall of my &quot;I love Me&quot; room, just never got around to it, despite my wife's harping, but I have a  lot of other &quot;things&quot; from that war hanging there.<br>
   If nothing else, I was involved in life---not protesting&quot; but doing something about what I felt was wrong, and the communist regime was wrong and evil, as evil as Hiltler's SS.  I would have fought them also.<br>
 I've stated that I hold no anamus against those who protested and paid the piper.  I do not admire the average protester however, because while they said they were protesting to protect the Vietnamese people, they failed the<br>
test.<br>
   In 1970 there were nearly a million protesters involved throuout the nation.  In 1971, about 30,000 and in 1972 no one. <br>
    Why, because in 1971 Nixon announced he would in effect, end the draft and the protesters stopped.<br>
   Can only reach one conclusion and that is the vast majority of the protesters were just a bunch of privilged college students afraid of being drafted.  Period.<br>
   Can anyone cite one protest---one--- against the communist governments as they murdered over a million?  So much for their concern for the people of the area.<br>
Joan Baez was the only one who protested and she was ostrazied by her former friends.<br>
